      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the comfortable end of your easy range. Focus on relaxed breathing and loose shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Conversational pace throughout. You should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradual wind-down. Let your breathing settle before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of easy walking or a very gentle jog to wake up the legs.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of gentle walking and light dynamic stretching — hip swings and calf raises are great choices.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your aerobic base builder for the week. Easy runs like this one are doing more work than they feel like — they build mitochondrial density, improve fat oxidation, and strengthen connective tissue without accumulating much fatigue. Resist the urge to push the pace; the value is in the volume at low intensity. Given your IT band history, pay attention to any lateral knee sensation and back off if you notice anything unusual.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Intervals at Threshold\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — your body needs time to prepare the cardiovascular and neuromuscular systems for threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval. Comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not hold a conversation. This is your 4:50/km threshold pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Active recovery jog — keep moving, let your breathing settle.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval. Same effort as the first — try to match the feel, not just the pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Active recovery jog.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third cruise interval. If this feels significantly harder than the first, that is useful information — note it for your coach debrief.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Slow to a comfortable jog and then walk. Let your heart rate come down gradually.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging. Include 4 x 20-second light strides in the final 3 minutes to prime your legs for threshold effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10 minutes easy jogging followed by static stretching, holding each position for 30 seconds. Focus on hip flexors and calves.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals are the cornerstone of half-marathon preparation. Working at your lactate threshold — 4:50/km — teaches your body to clear lactate more efficiently, which directly raises the pace you can sustain over 21 km. Three 8-minute efforts with short recoveries are challenging but very manageable at your fitness level. The goal is comfortably hard, not all-out. If the first rep feels easy, that is a good sign — stay disciplined and trust the pace.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This should feel almost too easy. The purpose is blood flow and active recovery, not training stimulus. Use the top of your easy range (6:27/km) or even slower if that feels right today.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — just start very slowly and build gently over the first few minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of walking and foam roll your IT band and hips gently.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your legs did real work yesterday on the cruise intervals, and today is about flushing out that fatigue with gentle movement rather than adding more stress. Research consistently shows that light active recovery accelerates clearance of metabolic byproducts compared to complete rest. Go by feel — if you need to slow down, slow down. There is no minimum pace requirement here. Given your IT band history, this is also a great day to include some lateral hip strengthening exercises like clamshells or side-lying leg raises after your run.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Full 15-minute easy warmup. Interval work demands your cardiovascular system be properly prepared.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First interval at 4:31/km. This is hard — controlled hard, not chaotic. Focus on form: tall posture, quick cadence, relaxed hands.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery. Do not walk unless absolutely necessary — keeping moving helps your body recover faster.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second interval. You should feel your breathing rate climb quickly. This is normal and expected.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Active recovery jog.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third interval. Focus on maintaining form even as fatigue builds.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Active recovery jog.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Fourth interval. If your pace has slipped significantly from 4:31/km, it is fine — the effort level matters more than the exact split.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Generous easy cooldown. Your body has done significant work and needs time to transition.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging with 6 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes. Strides should reach roughly interval effort for just a few seconds each.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"12 minutes of very easy jogging or walking, followed by thorough stretching. Include hip flexors, hamstrings, IT band stretch, and calf stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals at 4:31/km are your highest-intensity work of the week and the biggest aerobic development stimulus. Four 4-minute efforts is a conservative, well-tolerated dose — enough to drive meaningful adaptation without burying you before your long run on Sunday. The science here is straightforward: spending time near your VO2max forces your heart to pump at near-maximum capacity, which over weeks increases stroke volume and maximal oxygen uptake. Both of those adaptations translate directly to faster half-marathon performance. Key thing to know: the first rep always feels the hardest neurologically. Trust the process through rep two, and reps three and four often feel surprisingly controlled.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run — Aerobic Base Development\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":105,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":380,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":307,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at the very easy end of your range. Let your body wake up gradually — do not rush into your target pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":70,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":380,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic effort in the 6:00-6:27/km range. Conversational throughout. If you cannot hold a conversation, you are going too fast. This is the core of your long run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":307,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional progression finish at marathon pace (5:07/km) for the final 20 minutes if you are feeling strong. This is not mandatory — skip it if energy is low or legs are heavy. Its purpose is to practice running at goal pace on fatigued legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 5 minutes. Rehydrate and begin your post-run nutrition window.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of walking before you begin running. Your long run does not need a separate structured warmup — just start very slowly.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 5-10 minutes after finishing. Spend 10-15 minutes stretching key areas: calves, hip flexors, glutes, and IT band. Consider a light foam roll session later in the day.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday is your most important workout of the week. At 16 km, this run is a meaningful step up from your current 14 km long run — appropriately progressive without exceeding the 10% guideline when accounting for your recent training. Long runs develop the aerobic machinery that underpins everything else: fat oxidation, slow-twitch fiber recruitment, cardiac output, and mental resilience. The optional marathon-pace finish is a tool borrowed from Jack Daniels' approach — it teaches your neuromuscular system to shift gears on tired legs, which is exactly what the second half of a half-marathon demands. Fuel before this run, carry water or plan your route around water access, and take a gel or equivalent at the 45-minute mark. Listen to your body on the pace progression — the easy portion matters far more than the fast finish.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
